TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hansen, Stephen
AU  - McMahon, Michael
AU  - Prat, Andrea
T1  - Transparency and Deliberation Within the FOMC: A Computational Linguistics Approach*
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjx045
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 133
IS  - 2
SP  - 801
EP  - 870
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - How does transparency, a key feature of central bank design, affect monetary policy makers’ deliberations? Theory predicts a positive discipline effect and negative conformity effect. We empirically explore these effects using a natural experiment in the Federal Open Market Committee in 1993 and computational linguistics algorithms. We first find large changes in communication patterns after transparency. We then propose a difference-in-differences approach inspired by the career concerns literature, and find evidence for both effects. Finally, we construct an influence measure that suggests the discipline effect dominates.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjx045
ER  - 



